<LP>
   CHICAGO -- Rodman &amp; Renshaw Inc. said it signed a letter
of intent to form a joint venture with
Creditanstalt-Bankverein, the Viennese commercial and
investment bank, to provide futures brokerage services to
central and Eastern European investors.
   The Chicago futures and brokerage firm, a subsidiary of
Rodman &amp; Renshaw Capital Group Inc., said the joint venture,
CA Global Futures AG, would be 70%-owned by the bank and
30%-owned by Rodman. In a related transaction, the bank will
invest $5 million in the brokerage firm in return for 4.99%
of Rodman &amp; Renshaw Capital Group's stock and some
subordinated debentures.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Both transactions are subject to the signing of a
definitive agreement and regulatory approval. The
transactions are expected to be completed by Sept. 30.
   Kurt Karmin, Rodman &amp; Renshaw Inc.'s chairman and chief
executive officer, said the $5 million, which isn't required
to fund the firm's existing or planned operations, will be
used to retire existing debt.
   Jerome de Bontin, a managing director of Rodman &amp; Renshaw
Inc.'s financial futures department, will be co-managing
director of the joint venture, based in Vienna. The bank will
choose the other co-managing director.
