<LP>
   TOPPS Co. declared a 3-for-2 stock split, payable Aug. 1
to stock of record July 9. The board also boosted the
quarterly; it will pay five cents a post-split share on the
same pay and record dates. The Brooklyn, N.Y., maker of
baseball and other collector cards as well as Bazooka bubble
gum has been paying six cents a share. Topps will have about
47.3 million shares outstanding after the split. John
Perillo, vice president, controller and chief financial
officer, said that "keeping the stock price low gives a lot
more people an opportunity to buy the shares." He noted that
the company recently reported strong first-quarter
earnings.In national over-the-counter trading yesterday,
Topps shares rose 25 cents to $23.25.
</LP>
