<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Stiffer Sentences
   In Safety Breaches
   Clear Senate Unit
   ----
   By Albert R. Karr
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Senate Labor Committee approved a bill
that would impose stiffer sentences for criminal safety and
health violations by employers.
   The committee voted 11-5 for the bill, sponsored by Sens.
Howard Metzenbaum (D., Ohio) and James Jeffords (R., Vt.).
All the Democratic committee members and two Republicans --
Mr. Jeffords and Sen. David Durenberger of Minnesota -- voted
for the measure.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Separately, Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole is expected
today to urge that the maximum civil penalty for a violation
of provisions of child-labor law be boosted to $10,000 from
$1,000. In testimony prepared for delivery to the House Labor
Standards subcommittee, Mrs. Dole will note that the
department's Employment Standards Administration already has
boosted penalties as much as fourfold by considering
different violations involving one child separately, rather
than as a single violation.
   Two recent sweeps by the agency uncovered more than 2,800
child-labor violations, and more than $6 million in penalty
assessments are expected, according to her testimony.
   Under the bill approved by the Senate panel, employer
violations of the occupational safety and health law that
result in worker deaths would become felonies, rather than
misdemeanors. The legislation also would boost the maximum
jail sentence to 10 years from six months and the maximum
fine for such criminal violations under the worker safety and
health law to $250,000 from $10,000 for each violation. The
Justice Department says maximum fines of $250,000 a violation
for individuals and $500,000 for companies already can be
imposed under general criminal code.
   Under the Senate bill, willful violations that result in
serious bodily injury would become a criminal offense subject
to a jail sentence of as much as five years. And any federal
preemption of often-tougher state prosecutions of such
violations on murder or other charges wouldn't be allowed.
   The Bush administration supports the increasing criminal
penalties for employer violations that result in death and
the bar on federal pre-emption. But it opposes making
responsibility for serious bodily injury a criminal offense;
the Labor Department has said it is impossible to define with
any clarity what constitutes such an injury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0112
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900628-0112.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   NASA Finds Hubble Telescope Defect,
   Says Many Tests Are Now Impossible
   ----
   By Bob Davis
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   GM GMH WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- NASA has found a fundamental defect in the
Hubble Space Telescope that will prevent the space agency's
$2.5 billion eye-in-the-sky -- the most expensive satellite
ever launched -- from performing many of its planned
scientific experiments.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration said it
discovered that one, or possibly both, of the orbital
telescope's mirrors, manufactured by General Motors Corp.'s
Hughes Danbury Optical Systems subsidiary, was flawed during
manufacturing, making the telescope myopic. The agency said
it didn't uncover the problem during years of testing on the
ground. Over the past two weeks, NASA said, it learned that
the mirrors couldn't focus properly in orbit and wouldn't be
able to take images of distant stars and galaxies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It's a grim day for astronomy," said Maarten Schmidt, a
prominent California Institute of Technology astronomer.
   Edward Weiler, Hubble's program scientist, said that
astronomers wouldn't be able to use the telescope's
wide-field camera, the spacecraft's main scientific
instrument, for exploration and that they would have only
limited use of its high-resolution camera as well. The
wide-field camera accounted for 40% of the experiments
planned for Hubble during its first three years of
observations.
   The space telescope was launched April 24 by the space
shuttle Discovery. Astronomers had hoped it would help
resolve some of science's most fundamental questions and hunt
for such exotic phenomena as black holes and distant quasars.
But the spacecraft immediately ran into a host of engineering
problems that had the telescope aiming at the wrong stars,
shutting itself off and wobbling in orbit. NASA said it is on
its way to resolving those problems.
   But the mirror defect is far more serious because it
represents a fundamental flaw in the space hardware that
can't be fixed by changing software commands from Earth. Mr.
Weiler said that he hoped that a replacement camera, due to
be launched by the shuttle in about three years, would be
able to correct for the mirror's flaws -- comparable to
fitting the mirror with glasses. The mirrors, which are big
and fragile, weren't designed to be replaced. During the
first three-year period, Hubble would concentrate on making
observations of the ultraviolet radiation emitted by
celestial bodies, which are blocked by the Earth's
atmosphere, and obtaining data on the chemistry of these
objects.
   Mr. Schmidt said, however, that until Hubble is outfitted
with a new camera it won't be able to attempt to calculate
the size of the universe -- one of its chief objectives --
and would have a hard time hunting for planets around nearby
stars. Astronomers have never definitively identified a
planet outside this solar system. "There are many important
programs that can't be done or will be done with less
efficiency," he said.
   NASA said it believes the mirrors were designed properly
but were manufactured incorrectly because the surfaces
weren't properly measured. The agency said it is setting up a
board of inquiry headed by Lew Allen, director of NASA's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory. Hughes Danbury, which made the
mirrors, also blamed measurement technology and said it is
setting up a review panel. A spokesman for the company said,
"If the problem is in the {shape} of the mirror, it wouldn't
be as if we had a set of data and produced to the wrong
specifications."
   One scientist involved in the Hubble program said the
optical equipment used to test the mirror may have been
flawed. He said tests conducted years ago apparently had
given results that the telescope's mirror was properly
formed, when in fact it wasn't.
   At the news conference, Jean Olivier, Hubble's deputy
project manager, offered two explanations of why NASA didn't
catch the problems before launch. First, he said, conducting
a test would cost "hundreds of millions of dollars" and thus
wasn't thought to be worth the money. Then, he said, existing
instruments could have caught the imperfections, but for some
reasons they weren't used to make the necessary measurements.
   The space telescope's problems may adversely affect
another mammoth telescope the space agency is building --
this one costs $1.5 billion and will measure X-ray
emanations. This year, Congress approved $44 million for
early work on the telescope, but required that the mirrors
meet rigorous specifications. Hubble's mirrors were over
budget and behind schedule, contributing to the project's $1
billion cost overrun and delay in launching.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0111
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900628-0111.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:
   Drilling Oil Politics
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   As our Gerald Seib detailed yesterday, President Bush's
offshore-drilling edict was the product of extended political
calculation. The oil industry rightly objects to his
restrictions on their merits, but we suspect he got the
politics of the situation pretty near right. Given the
psuedo-environmentalist ethic now in force, little new
coastal extraction was to be expected soon in any case. Of
course, White House leadership on difficult issues is
welcome, but the greater responsibility in this case lies
with Congressmen and state officials, including conservative
Republicans, who formed a near-solid wall of opposition to
drilling; with judges, who've demonstrated hair-trigger
sensitivity to anti-drilling lawsuits; and with that segment
of the public that wants cheap gasoline but is intolerant of
the hazards of either tankers or less risky drilling
platforms off the coast. In time, as oil grows dearer, the
matter may become riper for rational choices.
</LP>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
