<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Industrial Stocks Advance 19.80
   Despite Concern Over AT&amp;T News
   ----
   By Craig Torres and David Wilson
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Stocks finished higher as investors bought up
blue-chip shares despite disappointing earnings news from
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 19.80 to 2862.13.
Volume totaled 146,620,000 shares on the New York Stock
Exchange, where advancing issues outpaced decliners 851 to
597.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   AT&amp;T stunned analysts yesterday morning when it announced
that second-quarter earnings, to be reported in midJuly,
would be below the $699 million, or 65 cents a share,
reported in the year-earlier quarter. Analysts had been
anticipating earnings improvement; in a recent poll of 11
analysts by Zacks Investment Research, the lowest estimate
was 68 cents.
   The stock finished down 2 1/8 to 39 1/8 on huge volume of
11,528,900 shares. AT&amp;T's composite volume was the third
highest of the year for any Big Board issue, and the highest
since 14.3 million shares of Amax were traded Feb. 5.
   "Everybody thought the AT&amp;T numbers would pull the market
down," said Richard Meyer, head of equity trading at
Ladenburg, Thalmann &amp; Co.
   But to the surprise of many traders, the AT&amp;T sell-off
didn't spread to other stocks. As a result, investors'
confidence rose, and they started buying health, drug and
consumer issues and other stocks of companies with a history
of solid earnings growth. Stock-index arbitrage buy programs,
where traders buy or sell stocks and offset the position in
futures to profit from price differences, also lifted shares.
   Among broad averages, Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index
rose 3.08 to 355.14; the New York Stock Exchange composite
index climbed 1.40 to 193.87 and the Dow Jones Equity Market
Index added 2.59 to 330.29.
   "Some of the consumer nondurable stocks, which look
overvalued, are getting more so because it is the safe place
to put money on a short-term basis," said Robert Stovall,
president of Stovall/Twenty-First Advisers.
   Drug stocks, many of which are trading at a higher
price-earnings ratio to the overall market, advanced.
Bristol-Myers Squibb added 1 7/8 to 63 1/4 on 1.3 million
shares; Merck advanced 1 3/8 to 84 1/4; Johnson &amp; Johnson
rose 1 3/4 to 66 5/8; Warner-Lambert gained 1 7/8 to 64 1/8,
and Eli Lilly climbed 1 5/8 to 81.
   Prudential-Bache Securities analyst Barbara Ryan told Dow
Jones Professional Investor Report she expects second-quarter
earnings for the group to be up 14% from a year earlier on a
10% sales rise.
   Humana surged 3 to 48 1/2 to lead a rally among
health-care issues. Manor Care rose 1/4 to 14 1/4, Community
Psychiatric Centers gained 1/2 to 26 3/4 and National Medical
Enterprises added 1/2 to 37 1/8.
   In the pollution-control sector, Waste Management rose 1
3/4 to 41 on one million shares. Browning-Ferris Industries
rose 3/8 to 43 1/2; the company agreed to sell used aluminum
cans to Aluminum Co. of America for recycling. Alcoa closed
unchanged at 63 7/8.
   Amid the slump in AT&amp;T, two other notable casualties of
earnings-related selling this week extended their declines:
Caterpillar, which fell 1/4 to 52 1/4 as 1.5 million shares
were traded, Dow Chemical, which dropped 3/8 to 57 on 1.4
million shares.
   But United Telecommunications, which went through a bout
of selling two weeks ago after PaineWebber lowered estimates
of the company's earnings, gained 1 3/8 to 38 3/4 on 1.2
million shares. Other telephone stocks also fared well
despite the selling in AT&amp;T; GTE climbed 1 1/8 to 32 and Bell
Atlantic added 7/8 to 50.
   L.A. Gear rose 1 1/8 to 27 1/4 after the company reported
earnings of 51 cents a share for the quarter ended May 31, in
line with its projection earlier this month of 50 cents to 60
cents a share. The stock had lost 1 3/8 points Tuesday as
market players awaited the results.
   PPG Industries retreated 2 7/8 to 46 3/8. This newspaper
detailed the environmental problems facing the company
because of chromium-waste pollution in Jersey City, N.J.,
where PPG once processed chromium ore.
   Fluor gained 7/8 to 46. Saudi Arabia's state-owned oil
company selected the company's Fluor Daniel unit to manage
the expansion of its oil and gas production facilities. Terms
weren't disclosed.
   Sotheby's Holdings dropped 5/8 to 16 3/4 after the
1989-1990 art auction season ended with a disappointing sale
in London, in which 58% of the artworks put up for bids
failed to sell.
   Elsewhere on the earnings front, Family Dollar Stores
added 1/2 to 13 after reporting that net income for its
fiscal third quarter, ended May 31, was up 65% from a year
ago.
   West Co. lost 1 3/4 to 17 3/8. The company said its
second-quarter earnings could be more than 50% lower than a
year ago because of production problems in the U.S. and a
curtailment of business in Brazil.
   Times Mirror dropped 1/8 to 31 1/2 after saying that
operating results for the second quarter "will show no
improvement" from its first-quarter results.
   Hunt Manufacturing fell 2 to 13 3/8. The company said its
earnings for the fiscal quarter ended June 3 were down 48%
from the year-ago period, and its hopes for record net income
this year have been "all but dashed."
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index rose 0.25
to 357.05. Volume totaled 12,350,000 shares.
   Bolar Pharmaceutical fell 3/8 to 5 1/8. Certain sellers of
SmithKline Beecham common stock filed a class-action suit
against Bolar over its alleged submission of fraudulent data
to the Food and Drug Administration to obtain approval for a
generic version of Dyazide, SmithKline's blood-pressure drug.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
