<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Bill to Reregulate
   Cable TV Clears
   Hurdle in House
   ----
   By Mary Lu Carnevale
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
FEDERAL COMMUNICATIONS COMMISSION (FCC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House Telecommunications subcommittee
passed a bill to reregulate cable television rates and
encourage new competitors to challenge existing cable
companies.
   Under the measure, which passed on a voice vote, the
Federal Communications Commission would establish the maximum
fee that cable operators could charge for basic cable service
consisting of local broadcast signals and public education
and government channels. Other cable programming would be
subject to regulation as well, but on a case-by-case basis.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The legislation would direct the FCC to develop criteria
to identify "unreasonable or abusive" rates and to establish
procedures for reducing rates that are excessive. Local or
state authorities could file complaints with the FCC alleging
that rates are unreasonable or abusive.
   The legislation also seeks to ensure that emerging
competitors to cable companies -- such as so-called wireless
cable operators and direct broadcast satellite service -- can
obtain programming. Cable programmers that are owned wholly
or in part by cable operators, for example, couldn't
unreasonably refuse to sell programming to cable competitors.
Also, cable operators couldn't require exclusive arrangements
from cable programmers as a condition for carrying their
programs.
   But the future of the House bill and of a similar Senate
measure is cloudy. Cable interests are fighting both
measures. "We intend to remain involved in the process, but
at this point, the question of whether a bill acceptable to
the industry can be enacted this year remains very much
unresolved," said the National Cable Television Association.
   Consumer groups, however, claimed a victory because the
House committee bill contains stronger consumer protections
than the cable reregulation bill that the Senate Commerce
Committee passed this month. "Consumers, satellite services,
broadcasters and others got their pound of flesh -- all out
of cable's hide," said Gene Kimmelman, legislative director
for the Consumer Federation of America.
   Meanwhile, telephone companies are trying to lift the ban
on their entry into the cable business. An amendment that
would permit cable competition from phone companies is
expected to be considered when the bill reaches the House
floor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0086
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900628-0086.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Horsburgh, Pioneer of Country Funds,
   To Help Barclays Unit on U.S. Start-up
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<CO>
   BCS WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A pioneer of the country-fund craze in the
U.S. has found a new home.
   Michael Horsburgh, who co-headed Bear Stearns Cos.'
international equity department for nearly 10 years before
leaving last year, joined Barclays de Zoete Wedd Investment
Management to launch and head its U.S. investment-fund
business.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As a senior managing director at Bear Stearns, Mr.
Horsburgh, 45 years old, was principally known for the
development of several funds that invested in securities of a
single country. His work helped open the field of country
funds to U.S. investors, leading to a frenzy among Wall
Street securities firms to launch investments in such exotic
markets as Malaysia and Turkey.
   Unlike early country funds that had focused on markets in
countries that had been closed to U.S. investors, Mr.
Horsburgh developed funds -- such as First Australia Fund and
Scandinavia Fund -- that invested in nations already open for
investors. He also helped launch First Hungary Fund.
   Mr. Horsburgh resigned from Bear Stearns last fall after
13 years at the big securities firm. But Bear Stearns
insiders say he was forced out after disagreements with top
Bear Stearns executives over the firm's international
investment strategy.
   For his part, Mr. Horsburgh said he left Bear Stearns
"completely friendly," adding that he felt it was "time for a
change."
   Two Bear Stearns executives with global stock experience,
James Sheehan and Dennis Baum, succeeded Mr. Horsburgh in
heading the firm's international equity area.
   At Barclays de Zoete Wedd Investment Management, a unit of
the investment banking and securities arm of British bank
Barclays PLC, Mr. Horsburgh will serve as managing director
and concentrate on launching an investment-fund business in
the U.S., largely for institutions. The unit currently
manages $35 billion for institutional investors in Europe,
Japan, Hong Kong, Australia and Canada.
   In an interview, Mr. Horsburgh conceded that the
competition will be stiff, but said there's room for growth.
"The use of international investments has certainly grown,
but it's still significantly lower for the average (U.S.)
institution than the typical institution in Europe," he said.
   The move by Barclays is part of a broad strategy at
increasing its U.S. presence. Earlier this year, the firm
hired several former Drexel senior stock analysts and support
staff to beef up its international securities business in the
U.S. The hires included economist Richard Hoey, investment
strategist Abby Joseph Cohen and financial-services analyst
John Keefe.
   Before joining Bear Stearns, Mr. Horsburgh was a partner
at Hoare, Govett Ltd., a London securities firm. He joined
Bear Stearns in 1976 as an institutional equity salesman and
was appointed co-head of the international equity department
in 1980.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0085
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900628-0085.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Collins Industries Contract
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   GO
</CO>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   HUTCHINSON, Kan. -- Collins Industries Inc. said it
received a one-year contract to provide ambulances valued at
about $12 million to the U.S. General Services
Administration.
   Collins, a maker of specialty vehicles, said the contract
gives the GSA the option of placing two additional one-year
orders. The company said that if the agency exercises those
options, Collins would provide a total of about 1,200
ambulances with a value of about $60 million.
</LP>
