900628-0073.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   AT&amp;T Says Net
   Likely Will Fall
   In 2nd Quarter
   ---
   Lower Sales of Equipment,
   Credit-Card Costs Cited;
   Stock Declines by $2.125
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   T
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., citing
lower equipment sales and the costly startup of its new
credit card, said second-quarter earnings will likely fall
below those in the year-earlier quarter.
   AT&amp;T's announcement knocked the wind out of the company's
stock and led analysts to lower their estimates for the
second quarter, as well as full-year forecasts for 1990 and
1991. Many also downgraded AT&amp;T stock to "hold" from "buy."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
AT&amp;T fell $2.125 to $39.125 on volume of 11.5 million shares,
making the stock the most-active Big Board issue yesterday.
AT&amp;T's normal daily volume is 1.8 million shares. The decline
also lopped about $2.34 billion off AT&amp;T's market
capitalization, given the company's nearly 1.1 billion shares
outstanding.
   While AT&amp;T said second-quarter earnings will probably be
lower than the $699 million, or 65 cents a share, in the 1989
period, the company still expects 1990 earnings to surpass
1989's profit of $2.7 billion, or $2.50 a share.
   "We expect to have a record year this year in terms of
earnings and our objective continues to be a mininum 10% to
12% {annual} increase in earnings," said Morris Tanenbaum,
AT&amp;T vice chairman and chief financial officer. While "we
think it will be difficult to hit our objective, we will make
every effort to do that."
   AT&amp;T's profit problem underscores the magnitude of
Chairman Robert E. Allen's high-wire challenge at AT&amp;T. His
campaign to slash costs, refine AT&amp;T's management structure
and protect the company's "golden-goose" long-distance
business has been highly successful. AT&amp;T had record profit
in 1989, and the company recently boosted its dividend for
the first time since the court-ordered breakup in January
1984.
   However, problems in AT&amp;T's office phone systems and
computer businesses continue to drain profits. Also,
potentially lucrative ventures such as credit cards and
international businesses are demanding huge start-up funds
and are years away from delivering the kinds of profits that
can offset losses elsewhere.
   Analysts were quick to point out that AT&amp;T's problem in
the second quarter doesn't portend a calamity. "This is far,
far, far from being any kind of a catastrophe," said Jack B.
Grubman, telecommunications analyst at PaineWebber Inc. "If
there's a silver lining in this news it is that the core
business, long-distance, is healthy as ever. . . . And while
the new credit card will cause short-term blips in earnings,
AT&amp;T has been signing up a boat load more customers than it
thought it would by now, meaning it will reach critical mass
to make money faster."
   AT&amp;T has signed up more than two million cardholders --
even after rejecting 40% of all applicants, notes Mr.
Grubman. The company recently said purchases with its
Universal MasterCard and Visa cards totaled more than $100
million, excluding revenue from phone call charges.
   Nonetheless, Mr. Grubman lowered his per-share estimates
for the second quarter to 58 cents from 72 cents, and to
$2.65 for 1990 from $2.90. For 1991, he now expects AT&amp;T to
earn $2.95 a share instead of $3.40. Mr. Grubman was one of
several analysts who cut his recommendation to a "hold" from
a "buy."
   "Investors have been paying a hefty premium {based on}
AT&amp;T's long-distance business," said Robert B. Morris III, an
analyst at Goldman Sachs. The announcement "refocuses the
market's attention on AT&amp;T's exposure to product life-cycles
and the economy {in addition to being} just a long-distance
company."
   Mr. Morris, who has had AT&amp;T stock as a "hold" for the
past six months, lowered his second-quarter per-share
estimate to 60 cents from 72 cents, and cut his forecast for
1990 to $2.60 a share from $2.80. For 1991, he expects AT&amp;T
to earn $3 a share, down from $3.15 a share.
   In the first quarter, AT&amp;T's revenue from product sales,
including telephone and computer equipment, increased 1.2% to
$2.72 billion. In 1989, equipment sales rose 1.7% to $11.5
billion, while profit margins flattened out and costs rose
6.1% to $6.97 billion.
   These numbers have led analysts to speculate that AT&amp;T
will have to dump some of its equipment businesses. Many have
long held AT&amp;T's communications equipment operations, which
include office phone switches and computers, to be
expendable. Mr. Grubman estimates that AT&amp;T's losses are $400
million to $500 million a year on business systems and $300
million on computers.
   "The equipment business basically stinks," said Mr.
Grubman. "AT&amp;T should take a look at exiting some of these
businesses."
   "A driving factor in PBX {office phone switch} sales is
company relocations," said George Kelly, an analyst at Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co. "When a company moves it usually buys a new
phone system, and with the real estate market down . . . this
is affecting AT&amp;T's sales."
   Mr. Tanenbaum said there are "absolutely no plans to exit
or sell" any of AT&amp;T's equipment businesses. And Mr. Allen
said: "Be assured, the anticipated lower second-quarter
earnings will not lead to any short term `fixes' that will
handicap the business over the long haul."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0072
</DOCNO>
