900628-0046.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Democrats Respond to Bush Tax Move
   By Offering Possible Spending Cuts
   ----
   By David Wessel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Democrats, trying to reciprocate for
President Bush's statement that tax increases are needed to
reduce the deficit, began offering possible cuts in popular
government benefit programs at bipartisan budget talks.
   "Tit for tat," said Senate Budget Committee Chairman James
Sasser (D., Tenn.). "They talked about their sensitive point
yesterday -- taxes. We talked about our sensitive point --
entitlements."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Leon Panetta (D., Calif.), chairman of the House
Budget Committee, listed a host of ways to trim spending on
entitlement programs, including Medicare, federal employee
pensions and agricultural spending. Programs for the poor
weren't mentioned, but participants said there was discussion
-- though no agreement -- about increasing federal income
taxes on Social Security benefits paid to upper-income
Americans.
   The Democratic proposals would trim spending on
entitlements less than President Bush and Republican
congressional negotiators have suggested. Negotiators are
aiming at a $50 billion reduction in next year's projected
deficit. The Republicans want entitlement cuts of $10 billion
or more.
   Despite the continuing differences, budget negotiators
yesterday engaged in what House Majority Leader Richard
Gephardt (D., Mo.) described as a "freewheeling" discussion
of other ways to cut entitlement spending.
   Republicans, even those who have criticized the Democrats
recently, went out of their way to praise them yesterday.
"We're moving in the right direction," said Sen. Phil Gramm
(R., Texas).
   When the budget talks resumed yesterday after a break of
several days there was a markedly different atmosphere, which
both sides attributed to Mr. Bush's statement on Tuesday that
"tax revenue increases" are needed to reduce the deficit.
   "The climate in there is pretty good -- for obvious
reasons," agreed Sen. Wyche Fowler (D., Ga.).
   "The whole tenor has changed. It is very determined," said
Sen. Pete Domenici (R., N.M.). "Whatever it was that kept us
from . . . seriously talking seems to have left the scene."
   One sign that the talks have moved into a more serious
phase was a demand from the Senate Finance Committee that it
and the House Ways and Means Committee, rather than summit
negotiators, decide what taxes to increase. But others,
including the administration and congressional negotiators
who don't sit on the tax-writing panels, insisted that the
outlines of a tax increase be shaped at the summit table.
   "We're going to work in tandem," said Senate Finance
Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen (D., Texas).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0045
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900628-0045.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Mecca Leisure Group PLC:
   Firm, in Reversal, Accepts
   Rank Organisation's Offer
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   U.MGR RANKY
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Mecca Leisure Group PLC, in an about-face from its initial
protest, said yesterday it will accept a #512 million ($890.6
million) bid for the company by the Rank Organisation PLC.
   Rank is a British communications and entertainment group.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mecca's board originally argued that the bid undervalued
the British bingo parlor, restaurants and resorts group.
   However, in its statement yesterday, the company said it
recognized it would be unable to reduce its debt
significantly in the near term enough to make its recent
heavy investments pay off.
   "Mecca would benefit from being part of a larger group,"
the company's statement said.
   It also noted that its acceptance of the Rank offer
stemmed in part from the temporary disability of its chairman
and chief executive, Michael Guthrie. Mr. Guthrie, the
architect of Mecca's acquisition-led expansion, is recovering
from recent heart surgery.
</TEXT>
