<HL>
   Senate Passes Omnibus Housing Bill
   After Debate Centered on S&amp;L Bailout
   ----
   By Rodney Ferguson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Senate passed an omnibus housing bill
after a day of rancorous debate that centered more on the
regional inequities of the savings-and-loan bailout than on
the merits of housing legislation.
   The bill, approved 96-1 last night, is a compromise
reached Tuesday by the Bush administration and key senators.
But the floor debate quickly deviated to the S&amp;L bailout as
several senators representing the Northeast and north-central
states charged that the bailout represented a transfer of
wealth from their states to the Southwest.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "When was the last time New York had this kind of
assistance?" asked Sen. Daniel Moynihan (D., N.Y.) as he
brandished a copy of the federal water projects legislation
that he maintained was heavily weighted to Texas and other
Southern and Southwestern states. He answered: "When we built
the Erie Canal."
   Yesterday's action continued the debate over who pays for,
and who benefits from, the $100 billion the U.S. expects to
spend on the thrift-industry cleanup, not including interest.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato (R., N.Y.) offered an amendment that
would target community-development funds to housing
jurisdictions based on a formula that takes into account the
amounts individual states will receive in the S&amp;L bailout.
The D'Amato amendment was offered in response to an amendment
by Sen. Phil Gramm (R., Texas) that would allocate funds
based on population, similar to general revenue-sharing
programs that were largely scuttled during the Reagan
administration.
   "To tie this to the savings-and-loan bailout is, pure and
simple, outrageous," Sen. Gramm said. "I have been offended
by the whole level of logic in this debate."
   Sens. D'Amato and Gramm ultimately agreed to turn the
matter of the formula for community-development grants over
to Housing Secretary Jack Kemp, who is to study the current
formula and report his recommendations to the Senate by July
1, 1991.
   At a news conference before the debate, Mr. Kemp called
the bill "the most significant step toward committing this
country on a bipartisan basis to combating the conditions of
homelessness, hopelessness, despair, and poverty that has
taken place in this town since the original War on Poverty."
   The compromise bill calls for outlays of $18.1 billion in
fiscal 1991, which begins Oct. 1., $19.5 billion in fiscal
1992 and $21 billion in fiscal 1993. It includes agreement on
four major provisions that had kept the two sides haggling
for the past three weeks. The administration won on two of
the four major points, including what it hopes will be full
funding for a home-ownership initiative that would provide
funds for public housing tenants to purchase rather than rent
their homes or apartments. The administration also won
changes in the Federal Housing Administration
mortgage-insurance program to provide a stronger capital base
for the fund.
   Additionally, agreements were reached on the eligibility
requirements for housing assistance, targeting more of the
funds to the very poor, and allowing housing jurisdictions to
fund new construction after they demonstrate special need for
new housing.
   Secretary Kemp acknowledged that the funding levels in the
bill are subject to change. "It is obvious," he said, "that
the budget summit will have an impact, not only on the final
authorization, but the final appropriation of housing funds."
   The House Banking Committee has approved a housing bill
that would be considerably more expensive than the Senate
version.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0026
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900628-0026.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   FASB to Postpone the Effective Date
   For Its Ruling on Retirement Benefits
   ----
   By Robin Goldwyn Blumenthal
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
ACCOUNTING (ACC)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NORWALK, Conn. -- The Financial Accounting Standards Board
agreed to delay for a year the effective date of its pending
rule requiring companies to account for costs for retirement
benefits other than pensions.
   The FASB, the rule-making body for the accounting
profession, had indicated it would make the rule effective in
1992. The latest decision would require companies to adopt
the proposed rule in 1993, although some companies already
have begun to recognize the costs. (Technically, the rule
would cover companies with fiscal years that begin on or
after Dec. 15, 1992.)
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The proposal is of great concern to many companies because
it will require companies for the first time to reflect on
their books the present and future costs of benefits -- such
as medical and insurance coverage -- that employees will
receive after they retire. The total is huge, perhaps $400
billion by some estimates. And the prospect of incurring such
costs has prompted some companies to decline to provide
medical and insurance benefits for retirees.
   The FASB has been circulating the "exposure draft" of the
proposal for comment, and hopes to issue a final rule before
yearend. The proposal has been in preparation for a decade.
   FASB Chairman Dennis Beresford said the one-year extension
reflected concern in comments from more than 400 companies
and groups. "We received information that it would be hard to
accumulate information, and to train actuaries. It would be
fair to give companies one more year to do it in an orderly
fashion."
   The group tentatively agreed to allow companies the option
of taking a one-time charge to income for benefits the
companies already are committed to pay. Companies that don't
choose that option could account for the accumulated costs
over a 20-year period, instead of the previously proposed 15
years. However, that language is subject to further review,
Mr. Beresford said.
   The previous draft didn't permit the option of recognizing
the costs all at one time. About 90% of the comments on that
issue favored permitting one-time recognition, perhaps
indicating that many companies will take that option.
   After recognizing previously accrued costs, companies
would take as an annual expense the estimated cost of
benefits to be earned in subsequent years.
   Most companies previously haven't reflected in their books
non-pension retirement benefit costs. Amounts paid to
retirees in the current year are deductible, but amounts for
future years for both retirees and employees are subject to
more stringent rules for a tax deduction.
   Nonetheless, some companies already have decided to take
the charge expected to be required to get it behind them.
Dallas-based LTV Corp. in late 1988 recorded a $2.26 billion
charge to cover its entire unfunded liability for such
benefits for current and retired employees.
   Despite the proposed changes, the FASB proposal still
presents major difficulties for many companies. "I wonder if
FASB isn't running a little scared," said Bill Miner, an
actuary in Chicago for employee benefits consultant Wyatt Co.
"The rules are very onerous, particularly to rustbelt type
companies, those that have a large number of retirees."
   Moreover, he said, many companies oppose the rule because
it will require assumptions that are difficult to make.
"Figuring out the rate of future medical cost increases is
one issue that looms out there," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0025
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900628-0025.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Hovnanian Expects
   Earnings to Decline
   For This Fiscal Year
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   HOV
</CO>
<LP>
   RED BANK, N.J. -- Hovnanian Enterprises Inc., a developer
of moderately priced suburban homes, said it expects sharply
lower earnings for its year ending Feb. 28, 1991, as the
sluggish regional economy continues to hurt sales.
   The company said it expects earnings of $5 million to $7
million, or 25 cents to 35 cents a share, on revenue of $290
million to $325 million. In fiscal 1990, net was $21.8
million, or $1.05 a share, on revenue of $410 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The fiscal 1990 earnings were 24% below fiscal 1989's.
While projecting a second year of decline, the company
stressed its belief "that fundamental demand for
competitively priced homes in the best locations remains
strong." In the past, the company has had up to 75% of its
volume in townhouses and single-family homes priced between
$70,000 and $130,000, which sold quickly, but such homes have
become harder to develop and harder to sell.
   "In the past years we had that success. People were
camping out, waiting on long lines -- we had to hold
lotteries," said John J. Schimpf, executive vice president.
But with layoffs and employment uncertainties in the New York
metropolitan area and a great supply of unsold houses in its
important central New Jersey market, buyers have become very
picky.
   "There's been healthy skepticism about housing prices in
the metropolitan area. A lot of the pent-up demand for
housing has been run out of the marketplace," Mr. Schimpf
said. Instead of cutting prices, however, Hovnanian is
offering buyers appliance packages and paying closing costs
to aid sales. Such incentive costs, along with declining
sales volumes, are depressing earnings, Mr. Schimpf said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
