<HL>
   California Sues Keating,
   Others Over Sale of Bonds
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   AMC
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- The state of California sued Charles H.
Keating Jr., several officers and directors of American
Continental Corp. and the company's former accountant for
alleged fraud in the sale of $250 million in now-worthless
bonds.
   The complaint, filed in Orange County Superior Court,
seeks restitution for bondholders and civil penalties that
could range from $50 million to $100 million. The suit is the
latest in a barrage of litigation seeking "deep pockets" to
repay investors and others in the collapse of Lincoln Savings
&amp; Loan Association, a subsidiary of American Continental.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The defendants include Jack Atchison, a partner in the
accounting firm of Arthur Young &amp; Co. who later went on to
work for American Continental. Arthur Young, which now does
business as Ernst &amp; Young, also is named in the complaint. An
Ernst &amp; Young spokesman said the company hadn't seen the suit
and couldn't comment.
   The subordinated debentures were sold through Lincoln's
branches, and the suit alleges that the company specifically
targeted elderly investors for the bond sales. The government
alleges that the thrift's collapse may cost taxpayers more
than $2 billion.
   James Feder, an American Continental lawyer, called the
suit "a waste of time and money" and said the allegations of
a policy to sell the bonds to the elderly were not true.
Lawyers for Mr. Atchison weren't immediately available to
comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0017
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900628-0017.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rostenkowski Now Favors
   Bill for Enterprise Zones
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- In a reversal of his position, House Ways
and Means Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski plans to
introduce a bill creating tax-free enterprise zones in
impoverished areas.
   The Chicago Democrat plans to hold a press conference on
the subject today, a senior aide to the chairman said. His
change of heart greatly increases the chances that some sort
of enterprise-zone bill will be part of any tax legislation
enacted this year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, particularly Housing Secretary
Jack Kemp, has been pushing a proposal to establish as many
as 50 enterprise zones in distressed urban and rural
communities. Investments made in the zones would be given
tax-favored treatment, costing the government an estimated
$300 million annually by fiscal 1993. But the
administration's proposal has been rebuffed in the past,
partly because of a lack of support from Mr. Rostenkowski.
   Mr. Rostenkowski's proposal would allow for fewer zones
than the administration proposal, but tax staffers said it is
designed to cost the same amount.
   The aide to Mr. Rostenkowski said it was a coincidence
that the Ways and Means chairman's change of heart came in
the same week that President Bush reversed his position on
tax increases. "The chairman has been looking at this for
quite a while," the aide said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900628-0016
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900628-0016.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUSH PROPOSED major initiatives for Latin America,
including substantial relief on the nearly $12 billion in the
region's debt held by the U.S. government. The policy also
calls for as much as $300 million in multilateral grants to
foster private investment, and foresees eventually turning
the entire Western Hemisphere into a free-trade zone.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   AT&amp;T predicted a drop in second-quarter earnings because
of lower equipment sales and the costly startup of its bank
credit card. The company's shares sank $2.125 on the news,
and many analysts withdrew recommendations to buy AT&amp;T stock.
   ---
   Democrats offered possible cuts in popular benefit
programs, in a move to reciprocate for Bush's statement that
he is willing to raise taxes.
   ---
   Stocks and bonds rose in further reaction to Bush's
statement on taxes. The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained
19.80 points to close at 2862.13.
   ---
   Japan and the U.S. settled most issues in talks on
structural trade impediments. Negotiators were pushing to
reach a final pact today.
   ---
   Leading economic indicators rose 0.8% in May after a 0.1%
decline in April. The index's second reversal in four months
lends support to the belief that a recession is unlikely, but
some worrisome signals persist.
   ---
   Suspected price-fixing by airlines is the focus of a new
Justice Department inquiry. United, Delta and America West
have been asked for information on their ties to the
industry's clearinghouse on fares.
   ---
   Accounting rule makers agreed to delay by a year, until
1993, the effective date of a regulation requiring companies
to account for the costs of non-pension retirement benefits.
   ---
   Fluor and Parsons won contracts to help overhaul and
expand Saudi petroleum facilities. Analysts valued each job
at as much as $5 billion.
   ---
   Siemens plans to invest more than $600 million in East
Germany in the next few years. Separately, Allianz bought 51%
of the nation's insurance monopoly for $163.1 million.
   ---
   A bill to reregulate cable TV rates and encourage new
competitors to challenge existing cable companies was
approved by a House panel.
   ---
   First Executive picked its ex-auditor to be chief
financial officer in a move designed to tighten internal
controls and to insulate Chairman Fred Carr from outside
contacts.
   ---
   The ties of all failed S&amp;Ls to Drexel and its former
junk-bond chief, Michael Milken, are being investigated by an
FDIC task force.
   ---
   The CFTC criticized sharply the SEC's conclusion that
program selling in futures markets triggered a 6.9%
stock-market drop last October.
   ---
   RJR Nabisco hopes to reset the interest rate on $2.6
billion of its junk bonds at 16 1/2%, a much lower level than
bond specialists estimated before the firm announced its
refinancing.
   ---
   Stiffer prison sentences and fines for safety and health
violations by employers were approved on an 11-5 vote by the
Senate Labor Committee.
   ---
   Laidlaw's founder plans to step down as chief executive in
August and resign as chairman at year end.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 146,620,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2862.13, up 19.80; transportation 1140.88, up 5.11; utilities
208.63, up 1.70.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3424.04, up
10.43.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 131.17, up 0.20; spot
index 131.38, up 0.31.
   Dollar: 154.45 yen, off 0.22; 1.6645 marks, up 0.0015.
