<HL>
   SEC Authority to Impose
   Fines Clears House Panel
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House Energy and Commerce Committee
approved by voice vote a bill that would give the Securities
and Exchange Commission the power to impose fines for a
variety of securities-law violations.
   The SEC's authority to levy fines currently is limited to
insider-trading cases. For other violations, such as
short-selling offenses or fraudulent sales practices, the
agency must choose between an injunction or barring the
offender from the securities industry altogether.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In addition to giving the SEC the power to impose fines,
the bill would allow the commission to impose
cease-and-desist orders against securities-law violators.
"This injunctive remedy would mean the SEC would no longer be
required to go to court to secure a temporary restraining
order or permanent injunction," said Rep. Matthew Rinaldo
(R., N.J.).
   The bill also would permit the SEC to ask courts to
prohibit people convicted of a securities-law violation from
serving on the board of a public company. Moreover, the bill
would let the SEC impose on violators fines of up to $100,000
for individuals and $500,000 for firms, or the amount of
their profits, whichever is greater. The bill is identical in
most respects to a measure passed by the Senate Banking
Committee.
   The committee also passed by voice vote legislation aimed
at curbing fraud and abuse in the penny-stock market. The
bill would, among other things, substantially increase
disclosure requirements for some penny-stock issues and
expand SEC power to bar crooked penny-stock salespeople from
the securities industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
