<HL>
   Florida Federal Fined
   $2.2 Million by Court
   In Student-Loan Case
</HL>
<DATE>
06/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FLFE
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. -- Florida Federal Savings Bank said
that a U.S. District Court judge in Tampa, Fla., ordered
Florida Federal to pay $17 million of restitution and fined
the bank $2.2 million for its conviction of student-loan
fraud.
   In addition, the bank said that the Office of Thrift
Supervision has asked it to enter a consent agreement.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Florida Federal was found guilty last month of falsifying
student-loan documents between November 1986 and May 1987.
   Judge Ben Krentzman also sentenced Robert O. Harmas, a
former Florida Federal officer, to two years in prison in
connection with the student-loan scandal. In addition, Judge
Krentzman placed James J. LaMantia, another former officer,
on probation for three years and ordered him to do 300 hours
of community service.
   "The court's recent decision defines a significant
component of the potential student-loan loss and, thereby,
helps clear the way for Florida Federal to be recapitalized,"
said the bank's president and chief executive officer, John
W. Sapankski.
   He added that "there are several investment groups
currently performing `due diligence' on Florida Federal, and
once the student loan uncertainty is quantified and settled,
we can look for investor commitments to be made."
   Mr. Sapanski said Florida Federal is also negotiating
settlements of the student-loan matter with the civil
division of the U.S. Justice Department and with the U.S.
Education Department.
   Mr. Sapanski said the Office of Thrift Supervision, which
has overseen Florida Federal under a supervisory agreement
for a year, has asked the bank to enter a more stringent
consent agreement, because its regulatory capital has fallen
below $15 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
